Get Data

id.calls <- "1gRoL7lZlwm7sreA5F9WbPoH5su4n4iGS"
calls.temp <- read.csv(sprintf("https://docs.google.com/uc?id=%s&export=download", id.calls))
fairfax.roads <- roads("VA", "Fairfax city")
fairfax.city <- county_subdivisions("VA", "Fairfax city")

Clean Data

calls.temp$date <- as.Date(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$dow <- weekdays(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$month <- substr(calls.temp$date, 6, 7)
calls.full <- subset(calls.temp, !is.na(calls.temp$lat))

Calculate Data

calls.year <- calls.full %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))

calls.type <- calls.full %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))

calls.type <- calls.type[order(-calls.type$count),] 
diffs <- diff(calls.type$PCT)
diffs <- c(0, diffs)
calls.type$diff <- diffs

Select Data

calls <- subset(calls.full, calls.full$type == 'LARCENY')

Analysis

The hour of the day has shown to produce varying hot and coldspots throughout the day. The locations of both remain relatively the same with the hotspots being located in the North East, Downtown, and South East regions of Fairfax. The coldspots are located consistently in the North West, North and Southern most region. From 3 am to 8 am there is no presence of hotspots but from 10 am to 6 pm there are three very active hotspots. With the increase in hotspots during these hours there is also an increase and consistency of coldspots from 11 am to 9 pm in the North West, North and South. When predicting future hotspots the locations will remain the same as they have over the hours of the day as well as by year. These are located in the North East on Blenheim and Fairfax Blvd, Downtown on Main Street, and the South East on Picket Road. During the hours of 3 am to 8 am will continue to have a lack of hotspots in the future. I predict that the cold spots located in the North on Plantation Pkwy, North West on Oak Place and the South on Roberts Road will remain the same as they have overtime.

The number of hotspots as well as the locations within Fairfax that are considered hot areas remain almost exactly the same for each day of the week. The hot areas throughout each day of the week include Downtown, the North East region, and finally the South East region. Sunday is the only day which produces an additional hotspot in the Western region of Fairfax. As for the coldspots, the North region as well as the South region remain coldspots every day of the week. The north most region of Fairfax can also be identified as a coldspot on every day except Wednesday and Sunday. Due to the overall consistency of hot and cold spots throughout the week I predict that the hotspots will remain in Downtown on University Blvd and Main Street, as well as the North East region on Blenheim and Fairfax Blvd, and the South East region of Main street and Picket Road. I predict that the coldspots will remain in the North region on Plantation Pkwy and Antietam Avenue as well as the South region on Roberts Road and Aspen Willow Drive as they have consistently during the days of the week as well as overtime. Although when comparing the hotspots in Fairfax overtime it would lead me to predict that the South East region will begin to cool off as it has since 2018 to the present. I also predict that the western hotspot on Jackson Memorial Highway, present on Sunday, will cool down as there has been little presence of this hotspot overtime. All other hotspots and coldspots have remained consistent overtime and therefore I predict they will remain in the same locations in the future.

Over all 12 months of the year, the number of hotspots as well as the locations have remained exactly the same. The locations of these hotspots have been in the Downtown area, the North East region, and the South East Region. The coldspots have also remained relatively consistent with the North West and the Northern most regions being identified as coldspots for all 12 months. The Southern most region remained a coldspot during all months but September and October. Due to the overwhelming consistency of the hotspot location I predict that those locations will remain hotspots in the Downtown region on Main Street and University Drive, as well as the North East on Fairfax Blvd and Old Lee Highway, with a small cooling down of the South East region on Picket Road in accordance with the yearly data which suggests that it will become a cooler spot in the future. Once again the coldspots will remain in the same areas as they have overtime as well as over the last 12 months with the Southern most region on Roberts Road and School Street becoming a more consistent cold spot.
